{
  "doc_id": "52475",
  "text": "Several epidemiological studies have examined the association between the IL4 VNTR polymorphism and the risk of cancer, including prostate, urothelial, breast, colorectal, and gastric cancers but the results are inconsistent. In a study by Yang et al (2014) IL-4 intron 3 VNTR polymorphism was found to be associated (2R/2R vs. 3R/3R+3R/2R, AOR = 1.46, 95% CI: 1.05-2.04) with early stage oral and pharyngeal carcinoma risk (OPSCC), which also interacted with alcohol consumption (p = 0.024) [CITATION_1] . 2R carrier genotypes (i. e. 3R/2R and 2R/2R) were reported to be associated with late stage bladder cancer in a northern Indian population [CITATION_2] ( [CITATION_3] . In a case control study involving 138 patients with transitional cell carcinoma (TCC) of the urinary bladder and 105 healthy controls from Taiwanese population, 2R/ 2R (RP1/RP1) was found to be significantly associated (OR = 8.88 (1.02-77.16); P = 0.018) with bladder cancer and tumour invasiveness [CITATION_4] . [CITATION_5] found no significant risk of developing cervical cancer with 2R/3R (RP1/RP2) genotypes in northern Indian women [CITATION_6] . There was no association of IL4VNTR polymorphism with the risk of Prostate cancer in a northern Indian population but two fold risk with progression to bone metastasis in prostate cancer was reported [CITATION_7] . No association of this polymorphism was found with the risk of breast cancer in a northern Indian population [CITATION_8] . No significant differences in genotype distributions or allelic frequencies of the IL-4 gene intron3 polymorphism were observed between the oral cancer patients and controls in a study from Taiwanese population [CITATION_9] . Similarly, in a case-control study involving 123 GC patients and 103 controls, [CITATION_10] found no association of this polymorphism with the risk of GC in Taiwanese population [CITATION_11] . In contrast the present study revealed an association between gastric cancer and IL4 VNTR polymorphism. To the best of our knowledge the present study is the first report regarding the positive association of interleukin-4 intron 3 VNTR polymorphism with the increased risk of GC.",
